INSERT OR IGNORE INTO projects VALUES('2018-014960','SFMTA - Third Street Transit and Safety ','','2018-014960PRJ','PRJ','Closed','2018-10-11','2018-11-13',0,'','SFMTA','','2018-10-11','','','','The SFMTA proposes to implement a safety project on Third Street, between Mission Street and King Street as shown on plans provided by SFMTA to the department in November 2018 and described in detail in the November 2, 2018 memorandum from SFMTA to the department. These documents are available as part of Planning Department case file 2018-014960ENV. Below is a summary of project elements that are described in more detail in the November 2, 2018 memorandum.  The proposed project would include the relocation of the existing colorized transit-only lane on Third Street from Howard to Brannan streets from its current position near the curb to a location near the center of the street. The proposed project would  relocate one existing transit stop at Harrison Street and remove one transit stop at Howard Street thereby reducing the total number of transit stops within the project site limits from four to three.The project would make no changes to Muni Service.  The project would involve restriping of the roadway and on-street parking and loading modifications from Howard to King streets. Capacity for right-turning vehicles would be increased, particularly along major access routes to the Bay Bridge at the intersections of Third Street with Bryant and Folsom streets. In order to accommodate transit lane relocation and additional right-turn capacity, capacity for through movements by vehicles along Third Street would be reduced through restriping Third Street, from Howard to Brannan streets, and Third Street, between Townsend to King streets (from four through lanes to three from Howard to Folsom streets, from four to three through lanes during the weekday AM peak period from Folsom to Harrison streets, from three to two through lanes during off-peak periods from Folsom to Brannan streets, and from four to three through lanes from Townsend to King streets). Up to 94 general metered parking spaces along Third Street, between Mission and King streets, would be removed by the project. The proposed color curb changes include 16 commercial and passenger loading spaces along Third Street, between Mission to King streets, that would be relocated on the same block face or immediately around the corner along the Third Street corridor within the project limits. Existing peak-period towaway restrictions (no parking during peak periods) would be extended (longer peak period no parking restrictions) on most blocks along Third Street, from Mission to King streets, or introduced on Third Street from Folsom to Harrison streets and from Bryant to Brannan streets.  This project would also include a number of improvements to increase pedestrian access and safety at intersections on Third street between Mission and Townsend streets, including: sidewalk extensions: sidewalk extensions at transit stops: conversion of low-visibility crosswalks to high-visibility crosswalks: new crosswalks at Folsom and Bryant streets, as well as across intersecting (with Third Street) minor streets that currently lack crosswalks (Minna, Clementina, and Stillman streets, and St. Francis, Taber, and Varney places): advance stop lines for vehicles at crosswalks: and upgrades to wheelchair ramps. Traffic signal upgrades on Third Street from Howard to Townsend streets would include right-turn-only signal phases with pedestrian movements restricted to eliminate traffic and pedestrian conflicts (and with right turns restricted at other times), pedestrian-only signal phases, and signal timing based on updated pedestrian speed guidelines.  An excavation depth no greater than 12 feet would be needed to install traffic signal poles, if existing poles cannot be utilized. The Department of Public Works would oversee repaving and island construction, sidewalk extension construction and traffic signal upgrades. Construction activities may require roadway closure but would comply with SFMTA Blue Book and Public Works requirements. Expected duration of constru','COMPLETE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2018-014960ENV','Closed - CEQA Clearance Issued','2018-10-11','2018-11-13','ENV',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO projects VALUES('2019-013425','DPW: Castro/Market Muni Station - Harvey','','2019-013425PRJ','PRJ','Accepted','2019-06-27','',0,'','SF Public Works','2019-06-27','2019-09-17','','','','The San Francisco Public Works (public works) proposes to reconstruct Harvey Milk Plaza at the Castro Muni Station. Harvey Milk Plaza is an existing plaza/transit access point in the City of San Francisco, Castro Neighborhood. It is bordered by Market Street on the north, Castro Street on the east, Castro Commons Condominiums (2425 Market Street) on the south, and Collingwood Street on the west. The site is triangular and approximately 279 feet long, tapering from 49 feet wide near Castro Street to 16 feet wide near Collingwood Street. The project site is approximately 13,000 sf. The existing site features curvilinear planter beds, a sunken terraced landscaped area, brick pedestrian footpaths, a flagpole with rainbow flag, and a bridge. The pedestrian footpaths create access through the site and provide access to two entry gates of 2425 Market Street. At the eastern end of Harvey Milk Plaza, a curvilinear set of stairs and an escalator provide access to the southern entrance to Muni’s Castro Station. The existing southern entrance to Castro Station is approximately 2,900 sf and features a gate to secure the station entrance at night, a circular bench, and a plaque to Harvey Milk on a column. A secondary stair and escalator entrance to Muni’s Castro Station is located on the north side of Market Street.   The project would renovate Harvey Milk Plaza and the southern entrance to Castro Station. The existing site would be re-graded, in-filled where necessary, and re-surfaced with stone pavers. The existing curvilinear planters along the northern edge of the site would be removed. The existing retaining wall would be retrofitted in its existing location running along the northern edge of the site. The existing flagpole and rainbow flag would be removed during construction and reinstalled on a new footing at its existing location. The existing curved planter and bike racks along with southern edge of the site would be removed and infilled to meet grade, and a new ramp would be located along the southern edge of the site. The project would provide pedestrian access from Castro Street to Collingwood Street and maintaining the two gate access points to 2425 Market Street. The existing southern stair and escalator entrance to Castro Station would be renovated. A new stair and escalator would located approximately 18 feet west of the existing stair and escalator location. A new transparent glass enclosure would protect the stairs and escalator.  The proposed project would also relocate two Path of Gold light standards short distances from their current locations within Harvey Milk Plaza. The light standards are designated as historic resources under Article 10 of the Planning Code, as part of San Francisco Landmark No. 200, Path of Gold Light Standards. The relocated standards would not be physically modified beyond being installed on new below-grade structural footings to replace the existing non-historic structural footings. The relocated standards would be brought into further alignment with the historic placement of Path of Gold light standards by being brought closer to Market Street and being installed closer to the grade of Market Street.  The existing bridge would be removed. The area under the existing bridge would be infilled to meet the grade of the third elevator stop and gently slope upwards to meet the gate access point to 2425 Market Street. Below grade, the southern entrance to Castro Station would be expanded from approximately 2,900 sf to 4,000sf by lengthening the concourse level to the east where the existing sunken terraced landscaping exists today. Project construction would require excavation of approximately 6,250 cubic yards of soil removal. The expanded Castro Station southern entrance would feature an art gallery and include permanent glass display cases, digital screens, and a large wall for permanent or temporary art installations.','COMPLETE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2019-013425ENV','Under Review','2019-06-27','','ENV','2019-013425EEC','Open','2019-06-27','','CATEX-EEC',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
