INSERT OR IGNORE INTO projects VALUES('2020-000332','SFO: Storm Drain Pump Station Outfall St','','2020-000332PRJ','PRJ','Closed','2020-01-08','2020-01-13',0,'Kim, David','SF International Airport','2020-01-08','2020-01-08','','','','The San Francisco Airport Commission proposes minor maintenance and repairs to timber structures supporting storm drain pump station (SDPS) outfall pipes, at San Francisco International Airport (SFO or the Airport). The purpose of the project is to maintain and repair deteriorating portions of the timber structures, which support the SDPS outfall pipes that convey stormwater to the San Francisco Bay, away from the airfield.   The storm drain pump stations at the Airport serve to pump stormwater into the San Francisco Bay. For drainage areas on the airfield with active aircraft movement (e.g., taxiways and runways) that do not serve apron areas, stormwater runoff is permitted by the Regional Water Quality Control Board to drain directly to SDPS 1A, 1B, and 1C where it is subsequently pumped into the Bay. In other areas of the airfield, stormwater runoff is first collected in detention basins and then any excess stormwater during wet weather conditions is pumped out into the Bay (SDPS 1D and 2/2A). The outfalls from the storm drain pump stations are supported by timber structures. This project would cover only SDPS with timber structures in the Bay (SDPS 1A, 1B, 1C, 1D, and 2/2A).   To ensure structural integrity of the timber structures, Airport staff and contractors perform regular inspections to identify any necessary maintenance repairs. Visual inspection of structural components from topside such as the timber deck and top portion of timber piles would typically be performed on land while diving operations would be conducted to inspect timber piles not accessible on land or submerged in Bay water.   Repairs may include in-kind replacement of failed or deteriorated components such as the timber deck platform, fastening hardware, timber bracing, and piles. Maintenance repairs such as carpentry and fastening hardware work on above water structure components, where accessible by land, may need a staging area adjacent to the shore. Maintenance of the timber structures would allow for continued safe operation of the SDPS outfalls, which drain stormwater from the airfield. This is critical because standing water on the airfield can attract birds which are a safety hazard to operational aircraft. All work performed would be in-kind replacement maintenance and no new structures are proposed as part of this project.  No in-bay boats would be required for repairs that can be accessed by foot. Construction would be completed with light machinery (e.g., delivery trucks) and hand tools. Materials required to complete the project would be delivered to the project sites via light-duty truck. For pile replacement, the use of boats and pile-driving equipment may be required. Any construction debris would be removed to an authorized location outside the jurisdiction of BCDC. Construction operations would be performed to prevent construction materials from falling, washing, or blowing into the Bay. If pile driving is required, construction activities would be limited to between June 15 and November 30 in order to avoid impacts to listed fish species. Other restrictions for pile driving would include only installing chemically treated wooden piles that are wrapped with an impact-resistant biologically inert material, only driving piles when currents are reduced, and using silt curtains during pile driving to contain turbidity.  The following approvals and permits are required: United States Army Corps of Engineers, Nationwide Permit under Section 404 of the federal Clean Water Act and Section 10 of the Rivers and Harbors Act: Regional Water Quality Control Board, Water Quality Certification under Section 401 of the federal Clean Water Act and the Porter-Cologne Water Quality Control Act: and San Francisco Bay Conservation and Development Commission, Abbreviated Regionwide Permit No. 1.','COMPLETE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2020-000332ENV','Closed - CEQA Clearance Issued','2020-01-08','2020-01-13','ENV',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO projects VALUES('2020-009718','Verizon/CBR/1 wireless site IFO 930 Clay','','2020-009718PRJ','PRJ','Open','2020-10-26','',0,'','The CBR Group','2020-10-06','2020-10-26','','','','Haight Ashbury 002:1247/035: 37.7646583:-122.4474398:930 Clayton Street: Steel Pole: SFPUC: V-K125 THIS IS AN UNMANNED WIRELESS TELECOMMUNICATION FACILITY FOR VERIZON WIRELESS CONSISTING OF THE INSTALLATION AND OPERATION OF AN ANTENNA AND ASSOCIATED EQUIPMENT. SCOPE OF WORK CONSISTS OF THE FOLLOWING: 1. REPLACE (E) STEEL LIGHT POLE WITH A (N) PL-300-050 POLE WITH 8-FT. SINGLE-ARM ASSEMBLY ON (N) CONCRETE POLE FOUNDATION. 2. INSTALL (N) FCC SIGNAGE ON (N) REPLACEMENT POLE. 3. INSTALL (1) (N) CANISTER ANTENNA INSIDE (N) SHROUD ON TOP OF 30’-0” TALL POLE WITH TAPERED “SKIRT” ASSEMBLY COVERING THE EQUIPMENT CONNECTIONS AND WIRING ON THE POLE. 4. INSTALL (2) (N) ANTENNA/RADIO UNITS INSIDE (N) HEXAGONAL SHROUD. VISABLE SURFACES ARE TO BE COVERED MANUFACTURER-APPROVED COATING. 5. INSTALL (1) (N) RRUS-4455 INSIDE (N) RADIO SHROUD. 6. WELDING: WELD PORTS IN NEW POLE TO ACCOMODATE ANTENNA AND RADIO CABLING. 7. CONDUIT: REWORK (E) STREET LIGHT PULL BOX AND (E) UNDERGROUND CONDUIT BETWEEN PULL BOX AND NEW POLE FOUNDATION PER SFPUC DETAILS AND SPECIFICATIONS. 8. PAINT: CANISTER ANTENNA, SHROUDS, MOUNTING BRACKETS AND HARDWARE TO BE PAINTED USING DURABLE PAINT (E.G. SHERWIN WILLIAMS FRAZEE OR EQUIVALENT). 9. SPACING OF SUPPORT ELEMENTS: SUPPORT EQUIPMENT (E.G. RADIOS AND CANISTER ANTENNA) TO BE VERTICALLY CLUSTERED WITH THE MINIMUM TECHNICALLY ALLOWABLE SPACE BETWEEN UNITS. 10. LOGO REMOVAL: ALL EQUIPMENT LOGOS, OTHER THAN THOSE REQUIRED BY REGULATION (E.G. NODE IDENTIFICATION OR SHUTDOWN SIGNAGE) OR PG&E REGULATIONS SHALL BE PAINTED OVER OR REMOVED. 11. SIGNAGE: FCC-MANDATED RF WARNING SIGNAGE SHALL FACE OUT TO STREET. 12. UTILITY LINES: PROPOSED UTILITY LINES BETWEEN EXISTING POINT OF CONNECTION AND SFPUC POLE TO BE UNDERGROUND. 13. PROPOSED FACILITY WILL NOT EMIT AND SOUND.  Work will be undertaken within the public right-of-way on replacement pole and will not affect poles that are decorative or historic in nature. Equipment is designed to be slim in profile and to avoid large bundles of visible cabling, equipment decals, lighting, or mounting systems so that adjacent buildings are not materially or visually impaired. Work will not physically alter any historic features or materials that characterize known or potential historic resources where these installations occur.','COMPLETE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2020-009718ENV','Closed - CEQA Clearance Issued','2020-10-26','2020-12-21','ENV','2020-009718EEC','Open','2020-10-26','','CATEX-EEC',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
