INSERT OR IGNORE INTO projects VALUES('2021-010648','SFO: As-Needed Airport Pavement and Drai','','2021-010648PRJ','PRJ','Closed','2021-10-18','2021-10-28',0,'Kim, David','San Francisco Internatio','2021-10-18','2021-10-18','','','','The City and County of San Francisco, by and through the San Francisco Airport Commission (Airport Commission), proposes as-needed pavement repairs to the movement and non-movement areas of the airfield portion of San Francisco International Airport (SFO or the Airport) property through the As-Needed Airport Pavement and Drainage Improvements Project (Proposed Project). The purpose of the Proposed Project is to repair and maintain portions of asphalt and concrete pavement on the airfield and to maintain proper stormwater drainage from pavement to prevent pooling of water.  The Proposed Project would accommodate as-needed pavement repair work within the airfield area of SFO. The Airport property generally comprises two functional areas: the airfield area and the landside area. The airfield area, or air operations area (AOA), includes restricted portions of the Airport dedicated to aircraft landing, takeoff, or surface maneuvering and directly related activities (e.g., runways and taxiways). The landside area includes the Airport’s surface transportation network, parking facilities, passenger terminals, and airport support buildings. The airfield area is separated from the landside area by AOA fencing and adjoining Airport buildings, including the passenger terminals.  Over time, pavement can fail from everyday use, resulting in deterioration, cracks, and bumps. Maintaining the asphalt and concrete pavement areas in good condition is critical for aircraft ground movement. Deterioration of pavement panels produces foreign object debris, specifically small fragments of pavement, on the airfield which could cause injury to staff working on the apron or damage to aircraft. Additionally, it is important to maintain the asphalt pavement in the movement areas to maintain drainage off the paved areas and prevent ponding on the airfield.  The scope of the Proposed Project would include the airfield area (project area is bounded within the Airport Operations Area Fence and shoreline). Types of as-needed activities include asphalt pavement repairs and concrete pavement repairs. Typically, small pavement repairs are performed by the Airport’s Facilities Maintenance, Pavement and Grounds. However, the Airport is seeking an as-needed contractor to perform larger pavement repairs outside the capacity of SFO Pavement and Grounds staff.  The reconstruction of concrete pavement would include demolition of existing aircraft parking (concrete pavement) apron panels and layers beneath, excavation down to 52 inches below finished grade, and laying of new panels consisting of compacted subgrade and aggregated rock and cement that meets FAA advisory circulars on standard specifications for construction of airports, including airfield pavement. For each area, construction activities could take up to two weeks. Construction would be completed with heavy-duty equipment (e.g., excavator, backhoe, skid hoe) and materials would be transported via dump trucks and concrete trucks. Hand compactors would also be used.   Rehabilitation (mill and overlay) of asphalt pavement includes shallow milling of the surface followed by overlay by 4 inches of asphalt concrete. Mill and overlay activities of an identified area would take place over 2 to 3 overnight shifts to minimize conflicts with aircraft movement.   Reconstruction of asphalt pavement would include demolition of existing pavement down to 46 inches below finished grade and laying of new pavement consisting of compacted subgrade, separation geotextile, crushed aggregate rock, cement treated base, and two layers of asphalt concrete. Asphalt reconstruction activities for an identified area would typically take 1 to 2 weeks of work. Construction would be completed with heavy-duty equipment (e.g., cold planer, asphalt paver, asphalt rollers, roller compactors, skid hoe, backhoe) and materials would be transported via dump trucks. Hand compactors would also be used.','COMPLETE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2021-010648ENV','Under Review','2021-10-18','','ENV',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
